<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRISTIAN SHOWS TALENT, BUT ACT NEEDS POLISH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ENRIQUE LOPETEGUI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Is Cristian, who made his U.S. debut on Friday night at the sold-out Universal 
Amphitheatre, a genuine talent -- or simply a show-biz phenom? 
</P>
<P>
 The 20-year-old Mexican sensation, son of soap opera superstar and singer 
Veronica Castro and himself a former child actor, certainly enthralled his 
mostly female fans with his performance, but questions remain. 
</P>
<P>
 Cristian (he only uses his first name) employed a varied and above-average 
selection of songs, especially ballads that exhibited far more character than 
the works used by most exponents of romantic Latin pop. The highlight was an 
especially sensitive, acoustic rendition in English of Sting's "Shape of My 
Heart." 
</P>
<P>
 The young singer exuded confidence and has put together a young and solid 
five-piece band. But he's still somewhat raw, showing limited command as a 
performer and often stumbling when trying to reach high notes. 
</P>
<P>
 The capacity crowd showed supreme patience, waiting nearly two hours for the 
concert to begin -- a delay caused by transportation problems involving 
Cristian's band, organizers said. 
</P>
<P>
 It was obvious when Cristian finally made it to the stage that he has some 
talent, but he needs to realize that he must work on both his singing and stage 
presence if he is to be more than simply a popular attraction. ENRIQUE 
LOPETEGUI 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112194-0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 100795 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
November 21, 1994, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 10; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
305 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MUSIC REVIEWS; WALTER PONCE PLAYS BRAHMS IN PASADENA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CARIAGA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On a good night, as seemed to happen at its opening concert in October and 
again Saturday back in Civic Auditorium, the Pasadena Symphony plays like a 
major orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
 Its music director, Jorge Mester, puts together brilliant programs, then leads 
them with panache and intelligence, often achieving the right chemistry.The 
ensemble usually responds appropriately. 
</P>
<P>
 Since its players are the cream of an instrumental talent pool unique to 
Southern California, and since the roster remains largely unchanged over the 
seasons, the results are admirable as well as reliable. 
</P>
<P>
 One variable among several, however, is the visiting soloist. That was the 
element that did not work Saturday and its non-workability caused dismay. 
</P>
<P>
 Playing Brahms' D-minor Piano Concerto on the concluding half of this 
performance, the Bolivian musician Walter Ponce delivered all the notes in 
correct sequence and with great and resourceful solidity. 
</P>
<P>
 Yet he missed by far any re-creating of the Romantic heart of this work. This 
was doubly regrettable since the orchestra approached so closely the 
warm-hearted, dramatic core of Brahms' inspiration in a strong and striking 
performance by any yardstick. 
</P>
<P>
 Ponce -- whose appearance and stolid, workmanlike playing recalls that of the 
late lamented William Masselos -- seemed to apply to the surfaces of this 
familiar piece cleanser instead of polish. So well-scrubbed was the solo part, 
it was as if there were spaces between the notes. Alas, where Brahms requires 
legato and long, arching lines, the soloist provided choppiness and 
sectionalization. 
</P>
<P>
 In the first half, Mester & Co. beautifully unraveled Kodaly's complex 
"Peacock" Variations; before that, they brought their considerable art to a 
probably unworthy project, Erno von Dohnanyi's poppish "Symphonic Minutes." 
DANIEL CARIAGA 
</P>
</TEXT>
