<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: TUSTIN; FAMILY NIGHT SEEKS TO MAKE MATH FUN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 How's this for family fun? Math. 
</P>
<P>
 Scott Singer, a fourth-grade teacher at Marjorie Veeh Elementary School, says 
that it's possible, even for parents who hated math while they were students. 
</P>
<P>
 With the help of another fourth-grade teacher, Mike Roth, Singer is 
coordinating a family math night at 7 p.m. Tuesday at the school's multipurpose 
room. 
</P>
<P>
 "We'll have game-like activities that involve counting, multiplying, talking 
about strategies and learning about algebra and geometry," Singer said. 
</P>
<P>
 The program is designed to get parents involved in improving the math and 
computation skills of their children. The activities could be done by the 
family at home, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Singer said schools that offer family math workshops have found that their 
students are enjoying math and spending more time on their homework. 
</P>
<P>
 About 30 families are expected to attend the event. Child care will be 
provided. For more information, call (714) 730-7544. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
