<HEADLINE>
<P>
ISLE-HOPPING TO AMERICA'S MAINSTREAM; THEATER: EDUARDO MACHADO'S 'FLOATING 
ISLANDS' IS A SYMBOL FOR L.A.'S CUBAN AMERICANS WHO SEE THEIR OWN STORIES 
REFLECTED IN THE DRAMA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAN BRESLAUER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Mark Taper Forum may be a long way from Miami's Little Havana, but lately 
it has become a gathering spot for Los Angeles' Cuban Americans. 
</P>
<P>
 The draw is Eduardo Machado's epic drama, "Floating Islands," the story of one 
clan's journey from Cuba to the San Fernando Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 Presented in two parts, the production comprises four plays, beginning with 
"The Modern Ladies of Guanabacoa," which is set in a middle-class Cuban home in 
1928. "In the Eye of the Hurricane" and "Fabiola" take place in the pivotal 
years of 1960 and 1961. And the final play, "Broken Eggs," unfolds in 1980 
Woodland Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 Filled with stormy domestic imbroglios and set against the backdrop of a 
country turned on its ear by revolution, the saga tells of one bourgeoise 
family's struggle, relocation and eventual assimilation into a new culture. It 
follows three generations of characters and takes more than six hours to 
perform. 
</P>
<P>
 It's based loosely on the playwright's own family history. Yet partly because 
so few plays about the Cuban experience have made it to mainstream stages, 
"Floating Islands" has become a symbolic moment of visibility for many Cuban 
American theatergoers who see their own story reflected in the drama. 
</P>
<P>
 One play can't, of course, be all things to all Cubans. Consequently, some 
feel it represents their experience well, while others are disappointed. But 
nearly all are pleased to see the presence of Cuban characters onstage. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a beautiful nostalgic trip," says George Hernandez, director of 
post-production at Paramount Pictures, who left Cuba at age 7 and lived in 
Miami until he was 19. "It was a satisfying tapestry of memories, reflective of 
a middle-class Cuban experience and also of my memories of my grandparents." 
</P>
<P>
 "Floating Islands" also reflects the Angst.  
</P>
<P>
 "I was moved by the play," says Al Nodal, general manager of L.A.'s Cultural 
Affairs department, who went to Miami from his native Cuba in 1957 and lived in 
Florida until 1972. "It captured the Cuban ethos -- the psychological torture 
that we all go through dealing with the loss of our homeland -- in an elegant 
way. 
</P>
<P>
 "The experience that we all share is displacement, and Eduardo did a good job 
of playing out the reasons for that," Nodal continues. "It captured feelings 
that we all have without getting overly political." 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, the response to Machado's drama has been more cultural than political 
-- probably because L.A. County's Cuban American population, numbering 
approximately 50,000, tends to be less overtly partisan than its Florida 
counterpart. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's more diversity of points of view here," Nodal says. "There's 
everything from people who support dialogue to die-hards for the embargo. There 
are some who support the revolution at this point, but a small amount." 
</P>
<P>
 Yet those differences don't seem to matter when it comes to "Floating 
Islands." And that is largely a matter of tolerance, especially when it comes 
to Machado's comparatively liberal agenda. 
</P>
<P>
 "Cubans in L.A. have a more open attitude," Hernandez says. "We don't look at 
it only as Castro/anti-Castro. There's more to life than hating Fidel Castro." 
</P>
<P>
 Then too, the left-leaning tendencies of the entertainment industry skew the 
curve. "There's definitely a Latin network (in the entertainment industry), and 
a lot of them are Cubans," says Carola Ash, director of development for actor 
and fellow countryman Andy Garcia's production company. "But because people are 
here for film, you tend to talk more about that than politics." 
</P>
<P>
 Those who have little firsthand knowledge of revolutionary Cuba do praise 
Machado for raising the general consciousness of that time and place. 
</P>
<P>
 "I enjoyed it very much, particularly the first two stories," says Ash, who 
left Cuba in 1964 at age 6, grew up in England, and has lived in L.A. for the 
past 2 1/2 years. "My family was not a typical case, because my father was a 
writer, so it wasn't like he had a business that was taken away. But I know a 
lot of hard-working people whose property was taken from them." 
</P>
<P>
 The one aspect of "Floating Islands" that consistently draws criticism, 
however, is the drama's prominent representation of homosexual incest. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are some rough things . . . but that is part of the plot," says Teresa 
Munoz Shaffer, who left her native Cuba in 1962, moved to L.A. in 1975 and 
works as an arts journalist for the Florida magazine Replica and the L.A.-based 
newspaper El Noticiero. "It had nothing to do with the revolution. It has some 
political things in it, but it's definitely not a political play." 
</P>
<P>
 Others feel that Machado's work fails to evoke the richness of Cuban culture. 
"It was lacking in a cultural basis," says Armando Castro, manager of 
Hollywood's El Floridita restaurant, a Cuban community hangout since it opened 
in 1987. "The music, literature and art is not in there. For being too long and 
sometimes boring, I would say it was incomplete." 
</P>
<P>
 In that way, he says, "Floating Islands" fails to counter the ills of 
assimilation. "Cubans here lose their culture (when) they come into the 
American stream," says Castro, who emigrated from Cuba to Florida in the 
mid-1950s. "The kids become Americans and go eat hamburgers. Eventually they 
don't even know what Cuban food is." 
</P>
<P>
 The absence in L.A. of a specifically Cuban neighborhood like Miami's Little 
Havana also contributes to the disjuncture. "Cubans in L.A. are all over the 
place geographically," says Hernandez. "We don't live in the same 
neighborhoods." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, the same factors that mitigate against a unified identity also make 
L.A. Cubans hungry for their native culture. "You're never going to find a more 
Cuban group of Cuban Americans than the ones in L.A.," says Hernandez. "Because 
we are so far away from Miami and Cuba, we are almost like double exiles. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are more appreciative of the cultural things because we don't have them 
easily accessible," Hernandez continues. "In Miami, it's in every corner. Here, 
we have to look for it." 
</P>
<P>
 * "Floating Islands," Mark Taper Forum, 135 N. Grand Ave., Through Dec. 11. 
Pay-what-you-can performances are being offered Tuesday (Part One) and 
Wednesday (Part Two) and Friday (Part One) and Saturday (Part Two). Call for 
complete schedule of both parts. $28-$35.50 (each part), $56-$71 for both 
parts. (213) 972-0700.  
</P>
</TEXT>
