<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: ORANGE; PRINCIPAL NAVIGATES TOWARD CHARTER SCHOOL'S 1ST 
TERM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLEY WRIGHT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Santiago Middle School Principal Mary Ann Owsley must resolve a host of 
weighty issues before she opens the county's first charter school next fall, 
but she is finding that the simplest issues can be the most controversial. 
</P>
<P>
 Students took three ballots before they agreed on colors for the mandatory 
school uniform, and Owsley said she anticipates a few struggles before everyone 
agrees to wear the white, gray or teal shirt with navy pants, skirts or shorts. 
</P>
<P>
 With that detail decided, school officials are putting final touches on the 
one-page contract that students will have to sign before they can attend 
Santiago. 
</P>
<P>
 The school became the state's 66th charter school in July under a concept that 
frees it from state and local control and gives administrators power over their 
own budget. 
</P>
<P>
 Owsley said she will meet with each of the school's 870 students and their 
parents between March and June to discuss the contracts. 
</P>
<P>
 "The agreement is really innocuous in that it just outlines the concepts of 
the charter," Owsley said. 
</P>
<P>
 Teachers will sign the contract as well and commit themselves to giving 
students a quality education in a safe environment. Parents must agree to 
involve themselves in their children's education and volunteer at least 12 
hours a year to the school.  
</P>
<P>
 Details are being hammered out in monthly Parent Advisory Committee 
discussions. The next meeting will be at 7 p.m. Nov. 30, in the school's 
library, at 515 N. Rancho Santiago Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
 "I want people to come in here with their eyes wide open," Owsley said. "We 
have to make sure our intentions are very, very clear." LESLEY WRIGHT 
</P>
</TEXT>
